Specifically, this survey asked the teachers, in addition to general information (such as gender, age, experience, etc), what  their feelings and preferences are with regard to the use of communication tools with students, and even using bots or chatbots in the classroom. In addition the survey asked about the most relevant \textit{Interaction media features} for the teachers with respect to the potential tool to use in class. 

The specific questions included in this second survey are listed below:

\textit{1. You prefer the interaction with your students to be ...}
\begin{itemize}
\item Synchronous: students and teacher/s in the same space, simultaneously
\item Asynchronous: the student asks at anytime, the teacher responds whenever possible
\end{itemize}

\textit{2. Regarding the interaction with your students, you ...}
\begin{itemize}
\item Prefer it to be done by institutional means/tools: office hours, forum/messages via the virtual campus, institutional email
\item Admit the use of other means/toosl: blogs, chat groups in messaging platforms, any others.
\end{itemize}

\textit{3. Which media features do you value the most for your interaction with your students?}
\begin{itemize}
\item Familiarity with its use i.e. that I do not need to learn a new tool
\item The official formation/training provided by your institution on its use
\item That only one-directional communication is allowed (from teachers to students)
\item Non-hierarchical tools that allowed teacher-to-student and student-to-student communication 
\item That allow additional functionalities such as interfaces to other tools
\item That allow teachers to develop/add their own functionalities (e.g. automatic correction tools)
\item That let me avoid to worry about maintenance and that it is easily sustainable from one year to the next
\item That allow to extract data to assess the student performance
\end{itemize}

